<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-27</title>

<p>This week's strongest signal is a shared conviction that world models are not just generative video toys, but deployable reasoning substrates—and that their main bottleneck is no longer architecture, but <b>how they adapt, plan, and know when they are failing</b>. Three papers make the case from different angles: a VLA that identifies its own camera and morphology through a handful of self-generated interactions; a latent world model that predicts action-prefix outcomes in parallel to make planning fast and less error-prone; and a large-scale empirical study arguing that world-model hallucination is a coverage problem with coverage-derived cures. Below, I investigate each idea with code and data; two additional shortlist papers round out the period.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> <i>Hallucination in World Models is Predictable and Preventable</i> is the most complete research artifact of the run—the authors release MMBench2, code, checkpoints, and a live browser demo, and the simplest of their three predictors reproduces cleanly on a laptop.</p>
</callout>

