<h1>Cross-Cutting Observations</h1>

<p>Two patterns cut across the deep threads. First, <b>world models are acquiring inference-time structure</b>: ICWM uses the context window for system identification, Fast-LeWM redesigns the planning query to avoid autoregressive error accumulation, and the MMBench2 work treats hallucination as a runtime signal rather than a post-hoc failure. Second, <b>coverage is replacing capacity as the limiting factor</b>: Hallucination shows that a 350M model fails predictably where data is sparse, and that targeted data collection closes the gap faster than scaling. The open question is whether these coverage-centric insights transfer to billion-parameter models and real robot deployments, where collecting ground-truth action labels is far harder than in simulation.</p>
